         <h1>Antonio Buero Vallejo, 83, Playwright and Dissident During Franco's Rule </h1>
           <div class="row">
               <div class="col-md-10">
 					<p class="text-left">
<blue>1</blue>Antonio Buero Vallejo , a highly admired Spanish playwright who made his name as a dissident during Franco 's long rule and who in 1986 was awarded the Cervantes Prize , the country 's highest literary honor , died on April 28 in a hospital in Madrid . <br><blue>2</blue>He was 83 . <br><blue>3</blue>Mr. Buero Vallejo , whose work was distinguished by a commitment to freedom and justice , was among a small circle of Spanish intellectuals who remained in Spain as dissidents during the Franco dictatorship . <br><blue>4</blue>Having fought in the Republican ranks in the Spanish Civil War , he was arrested in 1939 and condemned to death , but the sentence was commuted and he was released from jail in 1946 . <br><blue>5</blue>Theater was always central to his life . <br><blue>6</blue>He was born in Guadalajara , Spain , and enjoyed playing puppet theater as a child . <br><blue>7</blue>When he was a teenager , he moved to Madrid to study at the School of Fine Arts . <br><blue>8</blue>But his literary ambitions were interrupted when the Spanish Civil War broke out in 1936 . <br><blue>9</blue>His father was immediately arrested and executed by Franco 's forces , leading the young man to join the Republican forces . <br><blue>10</blue>The experience of war and prison influenced his writing throughout his career . <br><blue>11</blue>His best-known work , '' Historia de una Escalera '' ( '' The Story of a Staircase '' ) , written in 1949 and still widely performed , captured the physical and moral decay of Spain in the early years after the civil war . <br><blue>12</blue>Even though this work and subsequent ones portrayed the dark side of life under Franco , their performance was rarely banned . <br><blue>13</blue>In 1957 he was awarded the National Theater Prize for '' Hoy Es Fiesta '' ( '' Today Is a Holiday '' ) . <br><blue>14</blue>In 1962 he wrote '' El Concierto de San Ovidio '' ( '' The Concert of San Ovidio '' ) , a parable about blindness in which he portrayed Spanish society as depressed and paralyzed by fear . <br><blue>15</blue>Other works that reflected the hardship of daily life were '' El Tragaluz '' ( '' The Skylight '' ) ; '' El Sueno de Razon '' ( '' The Dream of Reason '' ) ; and '' La Fundacion '' ( '' The Foundation '' ) . <br><blue>16</blue>In 1971 , in the dying years of the Franco era , he was elected to the Spanish Royal Academy , an occasion he used to praise Federico Garcia Lorca , the playwright murdered in 1936 by Franco 's forces . <br><blue>17</blue>Mr. Buero Vallejo 's most recent work was '' Mision en el Pueblo Desierto '' ( '' Mission in an Empty Village '' ) . <br><blue>18</blue>Even after suffering a stroke in the autumn , he remained engaged in theater . <br><blue>19</blue>One week before his death he went to the Maria Guerrero Theater in Madrid to see his wife , the actress Victoria Rodriguez , perform in Friedrich Durrenmatt 's play '' The Visit of the Old Woman . '' <br><blue>20</blue>Mr. Buero Vallejo is also survived by one of their two sons ; their other son died in a car accident some years ago . <br><hr><br><blue>1(2)</blue>: <m_str>subsequent ones</m_str> (12_6) 	<m_str>their</m_str> (12_17) 	<br><blue>2(3)</blue>: <m_str>the Spanish Civil War</m_str> (8_8) 	<m_str>the civil war</m_str> (11_42) 	<m_str>the Spanish Civil War</m_str> (4_8) 	<br><blue>3(2)</blue>: <m_str>Madrid</m_str> (1_47) 	<m_str>Madrid</m_str> (19_14) 	<br><blue>4(21)</blue>: <m_str>he</m_str> (4_29) 	<m_str>Franco 's</m_str> (9_9) 	<m_str>Franco 's</m_str> (1_18) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (2_1) 	<m_str>Mr. Buero Vallejo 's</m_str> (17_1) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (6_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (8_2) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (4_13) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (10_8) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (10_11) 	<m_str>Mr. Buero Vallejo</m_str> (3_1) 	<m_str>Franco 's</m_str> (16_38) 	<m_str>Mr. Buero Vallejo</m_str> (20_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (7_2) 	<m_str>His</m_str> (9_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (5_6) 	<m_str>His father</m_str> (9_1) 	<m_str>Franco</m_str> (12_15) 	<m_str>His</m_str> (11_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (1_12) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (7_7) 	<br><blue>5(2)</blue>: <m_str>their</m_str> (20_14) 	<m_str>their</m_str> (20_10) 	<br><blue>6(3)</blue>: <m_str>Guadalajara , Spain</m_str> (6_5) 	<m_str>Spain</m_str> (3_28) 	<m_str>Spain</m_str> (11_36) 	<br><blue>7(3)</blue>: <m_str>Franco 's forces</m_str> (9_9) 	<m_str>Franco 's forces</m_str> (16_38) 	<m_str>the Republican forces</m_str> (9_19) 	<br><blue>8(2)</blue>: <m_str>San Ovidio</m_str> (14_17) 	<m_str>San Ovidio</m_str> (14_9) 	<br><blue>9(2)</blue>: <m_str>this work</m_str> (12_3) 	<m_str>His best-known work</m_str> (11_1) 	<br><blue>10(9)</blue>: <m_str>he</m_str> (13_3) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (14_3) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (19_17) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (19_4) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (16_24) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (19_6) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (14_28) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (18_10) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (16_13) 	<hr><br> gender:male	ethnicity:european<br>         </p>
